ur years of research at a Midwestern high school to examine the mercilessly competitive culture that drives students to advance. Producing Success reveals the many ways the community’s ideology of achievement plays out: students hone their work ethics and employ various strategies to succeed, from negotiating with teachers to cheating; parents relentlessly push their children while manipulating school policies to help them get ahead; and administrators aid high performers in myriad ways, even naming over forty students “valedictorians.” Yet, as Demerath shows, this unswerving commitment to individual advancement takes its toll, leading to student stress and fatigue, incivility and vandalism, and the alienation of the less successful. Insightful and candid, Producing Success is an often troubling account of the educationally and morally questionable results of the American culture of success.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aculture, cultural, high school, education, k12, america, american, united states, usa, middle, upper, class, classism, structure, society, social studies, privilege, background, inequality, equality, finance, financial, wealth, resources, economics, study, academic, scholarly, suburban, students, teachers, classroom, midwestern, midwest, regional, competition, ethics, achievement, parents, policies, administration, administrators, sociology, policy, institutional.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022614239540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226142425423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226142425/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-a